  "exemplar_id": "ex_hoarseness_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "58-year-old man, a longtime smoker, presents with a hoarse voice. He mentions it's been going on for a while but hasn't given a specific timeframe, and he hasn't said whether it's improving or staying the same. The doctor is deciding whether this is self-limited laryngitis from a cold or vocal strain, or whether the duration and his risk factors warrant escalation to direct laryngoscopy to rule out malignancy.",
  "good_next_question": "About how many weeks has your voice been hoarse, and has it been getting any better at all, or has it stayed about the same or gotten worse the whole time?",
  "rationale": "Hoarseness persisting beyond 3 weeks is the established threshold requiring laryngoscopic visualization of the vocal cords, because acute laryngitis from a viral infection or vocal strain typically resolves within 1 to 2 weeks with voice rest. Persistent or progressively worsening hoarseness past this window, especially in a patient with smoking history, shifts the pretest probability toward laryngeal cancer, vocal cord paralysis, or another structural lesion, and mandates ENT referral rather than continued empiric treatment or watchful waiting. This question is prioritized over asking about voice use or reflux symptoms, because duration is the decision point that triggers red-flag workup regardless of what else may be contributing.",
